x4freetext: PD-300 neutron generator
Three pellets, about 0.2 cm thick and 20 mm in
diameter were formed by pressing approximately 10
gram of CeO2 (99.99% pure) powder (natural isotopic
composition) at 980 Mpa. Each of them was sandwiched
between two standard Nb (99.99% pure, 0.5 mm thick)
and Al (99.999% pure, 0.3 mm thick) foils of the same
diameter used to monitor the neutron fluence via the
93Nb(n,2n)92mNb or 27Al(n,a)24Na reactions.
A 2.40 mg/cm2 thick tritium-titanium target, an
effective deuteron beam energy of 125 keV and beam
current of 200 uA.
A high-purity germanium detector (ORTEC, model
GEM 60P, crystal diameter: 70.1 mm, crystal length:
72.3 mm) with a relative efficiency of about 68% and
an energy resolution of 1.69 keV at 1.332 keV for
60Co. The efficiency of the detector was
pre-calibrated using various standard gamma sources
and 225Ra.
The neutron flux was monitored by a uranium
fission chamber allowing corrections to be made for
small variations in the yield.
Irradiation of the samples was lasted
approximately 2 hours with a yield about 3 to 4E10
n/(4pi*s). The groups of samples were placed at 0,
90, and 135 degree relative to the beam direction and
centered at a distance of about 5 cm from T-Ti target.
The cross section of
monitor reaction was obtained by interpolating the
evaluated values of the literature.
Corrections were made for the self-absorption of the
sample at a given gamma-energy, the coincidence sum
effect of cascade gamma-rays in the investigated
nuclide and in the counting geometry.
Total uncertainty
Counting statistics 0.5-25.0%
Standard cross sections 0.5-1.5%
Isotopic abundance 0.2-5.3%
Detector efficiency 2.0-3.0%
Weight of samples 0.1%
Self-absorption of gamma-ray about 0.5%
Relative gamma-ray intensity 0.1-4.3%
Half-life 0.02-1.8%
Coincidence sum effect of cascade
gamma-rays 0-5.0%
Uncertainties of irradiation,
cooling and measuring times 0.1-1.0%
Data were obtained from TABLE 4 of
J.Radioanal.Nucl.Chem.,305,691,2015
Compiled by Xi Tao (CNDC)
